          <text>
                    <body>
                              <pb n="1"/>
                              <p rend="align(right)">
                                        <placeName>St. Thomas</placeName>
                                        <date>Crev Shabbat Kovach</date>
                              </p>
                              <p rend="align(right)">
                                        <date>June 30<hi rend="sup">th</hi> 5608 (1848)</date>
                              </p>
                              <p>My dear friend</p>
                              <p rend="indent(2)">In the first place allow me to return<lb/> you
                                        many thanks for the very handsome form in which<lb/> the
                                        Road of faith has been printed and for the trouble you<lb/>
                                        took in superintending its execution, also for the
                                        trans-<lb/>mission of 75 copies for which you will be good
                                        enough<lb/> to make my <sic>acknoweldgements</sic> to our
                                        esteemed friend <persName>Miss<lb/> Gratz</persName>. If I
                                        knew in what manner I could make my humble<lb/> abilities to
                                        the parent Jewish Sunday School in
                                                  <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName><lb/>
                                        serviceable I <del>sh</del>would with much willingness
                                        undertake any<lb/> other little work that might advance
                                        Elementary religious<lb/> education, so admirably begun and
                                        continued that Institution.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">Herewith you will receive our new code of<lb/>
                                        Laws with instructions from <persName>Mr. Wolff</persName>
                                        how many are to be<lb/> printed. The written copy was done
                                        by a lad, yet I hope the<lb/> writing is sufficiently
                                        intelligible for you and the printer. The<lb/> marginal
                                        notes are, of course, to be annexed. Have them<lb/> neatly
                                        done, and have the goodness to use your excellent taste<lb/>
                                        and <sic>judgement</sic> in the typographical art, for which
                                        you are<lb/> so deservedly celebrated.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">I may say of these laws as
                                                  <persName>Solon</persName> said of his; they are
                                        not the best that could have been made, but they are the
                                        best<lb/> adapted for the persons who are to be ruled by
                                        them. Many will per-<lb/>haps astonish you, but on due and
                                        mature deliberation, I have no<lb/> hesitation in saying,
                                        altho' I am a party concerned, that they and the<lb/> labor
                                        of much thought, and have been framed to meet the
                                        exigencies<lb/> of a congregation so heterogeneously
                                        composed as that of <placeName>St. Thomas</placeName></p>
                              <pb n="2"/>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">Expedition is necessary in the printing of these
                                        laws<lb/> no doubt you will be able to forward them by the
                                        packet<lb/> which will sail from <placeName>New
                                                  York</placeName> in <date>August</date>. If you
                                        do, I shall<lb/> contrive to get you voted a piece of a
                                        plate, until we can give<lb/> you something better.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">I wrote you 2 months back by the Gt. Western.<lb/>
                                        Did you receive my letter? Everything here looks gloomy<lb/>
                                        owing to recent events in <placeName>Europe</placeName> and
                                        the civil war in <placeName>Venezuela</placeName>;<lb/>
                                        money has vanished, for the last 6 months I have recd.
                                        no<lb/> salary and even the latter has been reduced to $1000
                                        p annum.<lb/> I am obliged to have recourse to school shop
                                        again, but the<lb/> establishment has every appearance and
                                        prospect of success.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">My health is good, better than it has been<lb/>
                                        for years past, but <persName>Mrs. Nathan</persName>, her
                                        mother, and her aged Grand-<lb/>parent are all unwell.
                                        Your's, I hope, is not suffering from<lb/> the summer
                                        heats.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">Present <del>my</del> our best compliments and
                                        warmest<lb/> wishes to all our old friends. I long to see
                                        you and have a<lb/> few good chats with you and all those of
                                        whose kindness<lb/> we <del>I</del> entertain so lively and
                                        grateful a recollection. Congratulate<lb/>
                                        <persName>Miss Cousens</persName> for us, as we understand
                                        she has been or is<lb/> about to be married. In haste</p>
                              <p rend="indent(6)">Most truly yours</p>
                              <p rend="indent(6)">
                                        <persName role="author">M N Nathan</persName>
                              </p>
                              <pb n="3"/>
                              <p>
                                        <addressee>Revd. Isaac Leeser</addressee>
                              </p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">
                                        <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>
                              </p>
